    "recap_headline": "Ohio State Buckeyes | Ohio State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "SEATTLE, Wash.\n\u2013 Despite tying the game in the top of the ninth inning, the Ohio State baseball team (6-12, 1-5 Big Ten) was defeated by Washington (8-11, 4-2 Big Ten), 5-4, in the teams' series finale in Seattle on Sunday.\nGame Recap\nLee Ellis\nhad the first hit of the day for the Buckeyes with a double to left field in the top of the third, but he was left on base.\nThe Huskies struck first with a two-RBI single and a sacrifice fly in bottom of the third inning to take a 3-0 lead over the Buckeyes.\nNoah Furcht\nwalked to lead off the top of the fourth for the Buckeyes, followed by an infield single from\nMason Eckelman\n. A sacrifice bunt from\nAlex Bemis\nadvanced both runners. Furcht crossed home on a sacrifice fly from\nDane Harvey\nand Eckelman scored on a wild pitch to leave Ohio Sate trailing by just one run, 3-2.\nStarter\nPierce Herrenbruck\nwas electric on the mound. In the bottom of the fourth inning, he fanned three of four batters faced.\nIn the top of the fifth inning,\nMiles Vandenheuvel\nled off with an infield single, but he was stranded.\nAn RBI single for the Huskies in the bottom of the seventh inning gave them a two-run lead over the Buckeyes, 4-2. The inning ended with a great play at the plate, with a Husky being caught trying to steal home by Eckelman on a throw from his cousin\nHenry Kaczmar\n.\nIn the top of the eighth, Kaczmar led off with a double to right field. Furcht then reached base on a Washington fielding error. Eckelman grounded into a double play, but both runners were able to advance on the play. A single through the left side from Bemis scored Kaczmar and left the Buckeyes trailing by just one run, 4-3.\nWith two outs in the top of the ninth, Vandenheuvel launched his first career home run 376 feet out of the park to tie the score, 4-4.\nWith one out in the bottom of the ninth, the Huskies hit back-to-back singles to put two runners on. A run scored on a fielder's choice was the game-winning score for Washington.\nBuckeyes by the Numbers\nHerrenbruck struck out a career-high seven in a 5.2-inning no-decision. He gave up three runs on six hits.\nVandenheuvel led the Buckeyes with two hits.\nNick Sawyer\n(0-1) took the loss on the mound. He allowed one run on two hits in one third of an inning pitched.\nUp Next\nThe Buckeyes play at Xavier at 3 p.m. on Wednesday, March 18 before hosting Butler for a three-game series at Bill Davis Stadium March 20-22.\n#GoBucks"
  },
